Water line can reach as high as roof top of these ironwood-built shophouses. Theirs and the community's efforts eventuated a flood mitigation and drainage project by the government. Fast forward to 2025, the new Waterfront public space became the newest addition (circa Sept 26th, 2025) to an once abandoned historical place (circa 1840). The Sarawak Heritage Society Executive Committee for 2010-2012 gets a special mention for their work here.

Siniawan has two annual anchor events to highlight. The 'chap goh meh' (15th day of Chinese New Year) street parade is rooted in cultural (hakka) traditions. The other is the transplated root in the Siniawan Country Music Festival (since 2016).

The main street is now a mall where the pedestrain only stretch teems with street food stalls from Fridays to Sundays.

P/S Siniawan Night Market is a misnomer. Save for the odd fruits for additional revenue stream, one cannot buy fresh produce there. Dinner was a delightful adventure--I sampled all sorts of kuih and couldn't resist the tempting variety at the rice stalls, each offering mouthwatering local specialties. I wanted to try everything, but alas, my stomach had other plans.

The pork stalls were especially eye-catching, with cuts I rarely see elsewhere--pig face, ears, sausages, roast pork--sold at incredibly affordable prices. I skipped the fried chicken though; the queue was massive!

On a practical note, the heat had me running low on fresh clothes, so I grabbed some socks and undies while I was there. It turned out to be a great evening: delicious bites, a bit of shopping, and a good walk to top it all off.

The place was impressively clean, though curiously lacking in trash bins. Thankfully, one of the vendors kindly offered to dispose of my plastic bags. Update 2024/09/30.
The kampua stall is no longer in operation.

Update 2024/4/10.
Kampua here is still good and tasty and at RM5.00/plate, you still get a good stomach packing portion served.

Update 2023/12/10.
Old management is back, weird. I guess the previous batch of people were mere temporary. Anyway dining available after 7:15am, yeh! Oh, kampua mee here still is as good as before but now RM5.00/plate. Whereas the coffee, price of the smaller serving available now for RM 1.00, not great but very affordable.

Update 2023/09/01.
New management took over and the place no longer starts early, and according to the kampua stall seller, the best time to dine-in is after 7:40am or 8:00am.

Kampua here was good, not salty, not too greasy, straight strand noodles, the texture was nice, classic taste, a good serving portion and topping for the price of RM4.00/plate. Recommended.

Black coffee from the shop used to be okay but after the new owner stepped in, things went south, tasteless. At RM2.00/glass, I will order something else for a change.

Quite popular among older folks in the area, friendly owner, but inside space is a bit cramped.

Lye, Khaleel, CHAN","reviewer_id":"109901583439985965302","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/109901583439985965302?hl=en-GB","rating":5,"review_text":"Tamu Muhibbah is a must-visit spot in Miri if you want to experience the real heart of Sarawak! The market is full of color, and friendly smiles from local traders. You can find everything here -- from fresh vegetables and fruits to jungle produce, unique herbs, traditional handicrafts, and local snacks like belacan, gula apong, and Sarawak laksa.
